<h1>Use of the Causative-Passive</h1>

<h2> Formation </h2>

<ol>
<li> @N1{{}}@HI{{ha}}@N2{{}}@HI{{ni}}@Vsaserareru{{}}
</ol>

<h2> Definition </h2>

<p>
Causative-Passive indicates compulsion or permission. 
In the sentence pattern shown in the formation, it indicates that @N1{{}} was forced to do @V{{}} by @N2{{}} rather than doing it voluntarily.

<table class="sentence" border=0>
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{@FG{{@KJ{{plump^son}}:tarou}}@KJ{{mister}}ha@KJ{{before^life}}ni@KJ{{sweep^exclude}}wo@EM{{saseraremashita}}.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      Taro was made to clean by the teacher.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

<p>
It is possible to omit @N2{{}}@HI{{ni}}, but the basic meaning is unchanged.

<table class="sentence" border=0>
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{kono@KJ{{meeting^deliberation}}deha@KJ{{every^month^new}}shii@KJ{{question^topic}}nitsuite@KJ{{polish^research}}shitakotowo@KJ{{departure^surface}}@EM{{saseraremasu}}.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      At this conference, every month we are made to present what we have found out about a new issue.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

